mage_: use 'Claude dupond'.title() then... re.sub replaces only the leftmost... re.subn does more... since your proposition doesn't even work on 'claude dupond' (there is no \s left of 'c'), this is another good example for _not_ using re's btw: re.sub('(^\w|\s\w)', lambda m: m.groups()[0].upper(), 'claude dupond') does the job... title()'s nicer though

I think since we do it for videos, it would be inconsistent not to allow it for <track> but for <video src> ? if somebody changes the video's src half way through via JS, they would surely also need to change the <track src> that relate to that video I see yeah, I think that's fair enough 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I am writing a book on html5 video and am currently documenting content attributes - is defaultPlaybackRate a content attribute? yeah, but that confuses me with the defaultPlaybackRate, since it would make sense to set it as content attribute and then use only playbackRate in JS it's as inconsistent as the <source> elements are ok, thanks kill them all ;) does a change to <video src> blow away all the <source> elements? what's the use case? it's a big implementation and specification burden sure it is it's probably the main reason for not doing things e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: it's easier to use semantic markup than tables e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: so i don't buy that e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: but generally speaking, there are often cases where there are other even more important reasons to do something that override the "it's hard" reason not to do it e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: the question is here, what's the reason for doing it that overrides the reason not to do it? 040342c014ffc1c11592948bd92e3721: we don't do it for <source> yes, for <video> src we do it, but there's a good reason to support that (how else would you change the video?) e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: i'm having trouble imagining when a dev would ever do it surely they'd just blow away the <track>s and insert entirely new ones not mutate the existing ones just like with <source> i guess we can always change it later if there's a use case no the list of content attributes is in the spec in several places e.g. in the green box in the element's definition under "Content attributes:" or in the index at the bottom of the spec 040342c014ffc1c11592948bd92e3721: defaultPlaybackRate is the rate of playback, playbackRate is the rate you'd use when ffwding or rewinding e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: well, if we do support it... what happens to the TimedTrackCue objects? e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: seems weird that we'd suddenly orphan all those objects... e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: i can't think of any time we do that currently e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: would their .track be reset so you could insert them into an API-created timed track? that'd be even weirder... e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: there's lots of cases where we don't react to changes like this, btw, e.g. if you change the <base href=""> base URL, we don't reload anything dynamically e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: even though technically all the URLs in the doc changed e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: they're the new ones for the timed track API btw, should i name these interfaces MediaTrack/MediaCue or TimedTrack/TimedTrackCue ? 7e9ffbe20643381020df06acbfcae9bf, the <nav> element is not a replacement so much as a new, semantics-only element, so there are no rules on what it should be around, or what should be in it. If you add it, clients that understand "intention" expressed with things like <nav> and <section> etc. will be able to understand you better, but that's all they do. So no rules on what should, or should not, be in them in terms of HTML. Only on what they should contain in terms of "what the data represents" true. a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: Did you fail miserably? a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: Were the people marking your dissertation impressed by the markup? a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: I thought that's what you were spending all your time doing? :-) Type with other appendages gets an impression from the "Link rot is not dangerous" topic that namespace URIs are quite a fragile foundation so they suggest building other structures on top of that, like caching and redirecting and hardcoding override lists and reminding people not to accidentally let their domains expire and making local subclasses and I suppose it makes me wonder instead whether it'd be a good reason to not use that foundation at all (though I don't know what other foundations would be better) b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: They still suffer from a mild form of Link Rot, because if I start using com.example.foo and then accidentally let com.example expire and someone else registers it and builds a new application based on that domain then they might conflict with my names and people will think my names belong to them The problem is that an object with a certain lifetime is depending on an object with a potentially shorter lifetime and C++ teaches us that such relationships will eventually cause horrible pain and memory corruption That too I wonder if all the com.sun.* Java classes will be renamed to com.oracle.* Has anyone (in distributed systems in general, not just the web) solved the problem of having identifiers that are globally unique and eternally unique, and that don't depend on a centralised registry, and that are human-readable? (I suppose I consider mildly distributed registries, like the IP number assignment system, to be similar enough to a centralised registry that it's not acceptable either) If not, I guess the question is which of those requirements to sacrifice But Python lets you manually override the mapping from identifier to implementation (e.g. by changing PYTHONPATH or moving libraries into the current directory) if you need to resolve conflicts in exceptional cases just like XML Namespace prefixes do Without some mechanism for conflict resolution, it's not a robust way to avoid problems caused by naming conflicts It's not terribly unlikely that I would e.g. create a physics simulation program with a file called "atom.py" containing my Atom class, and say "import atom" and it would collide with the 'atom' package (for RFC 4287 style Atom) (The conflict there is easily resolved because Python will look for ./atom.py before it looks for /usr/lib/python2.5/site-packages/atom, if I remember correctly) Why is it false security? (as opposed to unnecessary (but true) security) "link rot within the RDF world is an extremely rare and unlikely occurrence" That sounds like a testable observation and the test seems to refute that observation I see several 404s and several servers-not-responding, from the few dozen mosts common RDF namespace URIs s/mosts/most/ (There are so many servers-not-responding that my download script is taking forever :-/ ) I really should have reduced curl's timeout

Python package names seem to strike a good balance I think python package names, or java FQNs, etc. provide enough disambiguation People seem to want more disambiguation than they really need, to get some kind of warm-fuzzy feeling of false security But given author error, cut-and-paste, etc. the straightjacket solutions to disambiguation don't really get you any more disambiguation than the "sufficiently-interesting prefix" solution

Oh, maybe that was just for the short names It doesn't sound like a complex explanation to me - there's always a lot of known bugs and issues, which will be resolved over time, and any publication is necessarily a snapshot at a time when some have not yet been resolved It'd be better if it didn't take six months to publish the next snapshot, though I don't think the W3C staff would appreciate having to go through the publication process for every CVS commit and given the W3C's requirement that something is published regularly, the publication process can't be ignored entirely but the published snapshots shouldn't lag so much behind the editors' drafts a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: The HTML WG already seems incompatible with heartbeat Anyway, delaying an already-slow publication cycle for a good moment would be bad, but publishing regularly whenever there's a good moment would be good and better satisfy the heartbeat desires a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: Maybe increasing frequency would lower overhead e.g. people wouldn't bother objecting to publication of the new draft, when it's not changed much since the draft that was published a month ago b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: That seems like a positive feedback loop People think publication is important, so they fight to delay it a bit and so it takes much longer and since publication takes much longer, each snapshot hangs around for a long time and becomes more important So the solution is to break the loop by forcing a few quick publication cycles s/the/a/ and then people will realise it doesn't matter if this version isn't perfect, there'll be another version coming along soon

it would have been nice if the published WD didn't contain stuff we already agreed should be removed, but I guess I'll have to wait for the next draft then (and in the meantime explain to outsiders why we publish stuff we  agreed to drop) "hyperlink auditing" published WDs are very important for people outside the W3C/WhatWG lookinh g people outside the process want to get a signal "please look now", not following commits also, they want something stable to comment on deal with it that also means that a good moment to publish is when there was a significant change or improvement therefore getting the change applied for ISSUE-1 and 2 would have been good 3f2e2531201cfbf853f16f668132eaf2, exactly

In fact we could just take the limit as t->0 and not bother with snapshots at all 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28: All the people outside the process I have encountered have been horribly confused by the snapshots since they are always out of date 3f2e2531201cfbf853f16f668132eaf2: Sure, I'm not suggesting that it would work with the current W3C rules but presumably the rules are a means to an end rather than an end unto themselves I would like some evidence to back up "people want" 3f2e2531201cfbf853f16f668132eaf2: That was roughly the original plan, but it turns out that people are confused into thinking that publication is somehow meaningful and so fight tooth and nail for their changes to be taken before publication even though the snapshot is useless 3f2e2531201cfbf853f16f668132eaf2: Apart from the bit about snapshots being more important (they are posibly percieved as more important but are actually less important the longer lived they are), that is exactly what has happened The loop could be broken by making publication strictly date based But people wouldn't like that because it would be obvious that it is pointless
"good moment to publish" seems incompatible with heartbeat 3f2e2531201cfbf853f16f668132eaf2: The overhead of doing a publication seems incompatible with a higher frequency, though

wiesen_: Those tags are part of the protocol, not the data. They're not supposed to be seen by anything above the protocol layer. If you HTTP client delivers them to your application the HTTP client is not a proper HTTP client. wiesen_: what program gives you "336c[[jsondata]] 0"? A web browser? Or a custom HTTP client program? Nope, I usually use snoop, tcpdump or ethereal when debugging protocol-layer problems. =) But anyway, why are the chunked encoding tags a problem? They're a part of the protocol, and are not part of the output from the protocol. If you actually see them from a client, the client is broken. The fact that they're there during HTTP transfer is perfectly normal =) And what client do you use? telnet? =) Do you see chunked-encoding tags in the browser as well? wiesen_: See what I said at 10:17 wiesen_: The browser understands HTTP and decodes chunked encoding appropriately. Say HTML 6 adds a new void element. How would an HTML 5 parser know that the rest of the document isn't a child of that element? That seems problematic. Any new void element then creates a chicken & egg problem. Authors won't adopt it because they can't use it in a progressive enhancement safe way since it corrupts the DOM. Agents won't add it because authors don't use it. Similar situation to XHTML 2. People are jumping in and using section/header/footer/etc now without proper browser support. Not if they're serving as text/html ;) As for the past, there's never been a time where HTML was actively evolving with so many authors and authoring programs. ‚Ä¶as we have today I'd propose that HTML 5 parsing treat unrecognized elements (and only unrecognized elements) similar to foreign elements, where the SOLIDUS marks the start tag as self-closing. Author adoption of new void elements. When <area> was first introduce, authors would add an image map to their site but also provide supplemental navigation below the image. Authors were able to adopt the element before all agents supported it. You can't know that all new void elements will have a mandatory parent element. Didn't realize span was unknown to the parser. Why is that? ah, like void elements :) One of the solutions offered on the mailing list back in August was to have not add any new void elements. Not a fan of the idea, would just lead to more cases like <script src=# /> I can see how not allowing new void elements would lead to elements with empty content models instead, which then authors would just try to self-close (like with script src) causing more problems in the end.

oh, the widget uri scheme discussion got a whole lot harder there is one case where we can't avoid exposing it externally cross-document messaging yes the origin attr is a URI, iirc The origin attribute represents, in server-sent events and cross-document messaging, the origin of the document that sent the message (typically the scheme, hostname, and port of the document, but not its path or fragment identifier). 8d52bf87a239352ba7cc0aba1035e393: not between widgets between web pages and widgets <iframe> inside a widget would you ever want to know that the origin was a widget? and not some other, undiscoverable origin e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0 mind pointing to the multipage version? does 'null' qualify as an opaque identifier in this case? 8d52bf87a239352ba7cc0aba1035e393: the origin then is a guid except if you want to have interaction between web and widget, and authoratively at least know that something is a widget 8d52bf87a239352ba7cc0aba1035e393: chrome extensions as in "Compatible with Google chrome"? or as in "unspecified extensions for the browser chrome, a la jetpack" what I really don't get with this origin bit is the origin attribute is specified as a DOMString, then it _will_ be null for comparison purposes (which is e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0's point)

postMessage? postMessage only needs an origin, not a URI no origin can be a URI *or* a non-URI string. it's the latter for things like sandboxed iframes. or script from data: URIs of course, the other question is how one widget gets hold of another widget's window object in the first place *typically* right in which case things should work out perfectly nicely ??? no no for widgets, it would be a random string that's the point whoops, where's that? step back, more explicit e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0, ref? thx woah, safari 4 beta doesn't behave that nicely on really large documents http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/browsers.html#origin http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/comms.html#posting-messages e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0, the serialization isn't relevant for postMessage as postMessage refers to the same origin definition http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/browsers.html#same-origin If A and B are both opaque identifiers, and their value is equal, then return true. therefore, as long as the iframe follows the pattern of just calling postMessage back with the .origin attribute it was handed in the first place, all should be fine null is what you get when you serialize it isn't the opaque identifier itself so the one thing that possibly needs clarification is whether, when ".origin" is passed into postMessage, an opaque identifier survives That's a genuine HTML5 spec question, and needs solving there. 85793dd1775fbc0c0562493f069bcaa2, yes my point is that it doesn't need to be tied to the widget URI scheme (one of the reasons why I don't like that tying is that this would be a URI scheme for which you can never write down an absolute URI -- violates principle of least surprise) in that case, you'd probably want to know a bit more about the widget like, from whom it came Adam Barth tells me that Mozilla is playing with chrome extensions and doing interesting things with putting public key fingerprints into origins. I think he'll send a note to public-webapps about that soon. as in Mozilla chrome extensions don't know about compatible with Google chrome, and had parsed this as unrelated to it I understood this to be the latter e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0, on what this time? ;-) chuckles yes argh overlooked that piece, and suspect that it's a bug in html5 ;-) look, the reason for targetOrigin is to make sure that the target window of a postMessage hasn't been navigated elsewhere for the origin attribute on the MessageEvent, you've got two purposes: 1. feed into targetOrigin when responding. In this case, it's fine to just pass through an opaque origin 2. compare to some string that you know of.  In this case, you'll actually want to do the serialization so, what I'm saying is that origin is cast to DOMString too early in the spec since you break the ability to pass messages back to anything that had a synthetic origin why? depends on the use case you might very well be exposing a public API not necessarily I might very well want to send a response to the precise guy from whom the question came, to not leak their private information to a third party without caring who they are being able to pass through origin even when it's an opaque identifier gives me that ability casting to DOMstring earlier breaks it therefore, spec bug (and yes, you're totally right about the "compare to some known URI" use case for having a string representation -- not disputing that) yes lol http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-html/2009May/0478.html

aha, it doesn't actually define any elements or attributes so I don't need to do anything, since I don't care about content models Hmm, I should drop the "only in HTML4 Strict" because there isn't actually anything that's only in HTML4 Strict Oh, and I got some of the Transitional bits wrong since I hard-coded entity lists... http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/misc/htmldiffs.txt - now updated to be more concise and hopefully more correct The HTML5 Differences document seems quite inconsistent in how it talks about de-deprecated attributes - it makes it sound like <base target> is new and <a target> was just resurrected, except the Transitional DTD seems to treat both identically a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: Yes, as long as it's not a random HTML document you pulled off the web because then the chances would be good that it'll be unserialisable as XML http://html5.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/spec-splitter/to-xhtml5.py converts it to XHTML5, and you can skip some bits if you just want generic XML It's trivial to install from SVN - just rename the 'src' directory to 'html5lib', then stick it in the directory you're working in, then "import html5lib" should pick it up (Maybe that's not the official installation route, but it works for me...) doesn't see why anyone would want the spec as XML when you can just parse it with regular expressions ;-) The pumping lemma is no problem if you're using Perl regexps - the documentation even has an example of how to match correctly parenthesised strings :-) Oh, whoops, still had missing bits in htmldiffs.txt... how do you change colors in vim? I downloaded http://vim.sourceforge.net/scripts/script.php?script_id=625 how do I get to the themes menu? oh. ok ok I have found a color scheme that I like. Now how do I make that the default ok is there a way to have different color schemes for different source files. for exampel scheme a for c files, scheme b for html files, etc...

:hilight <Name_of_the_style> ctermfg=? ctermbg=? guifg=? guibg=? cterm=? gui=? term=? Name of the style is for example "Identifier" or any other type that may present itself in the syntax, Normal for normal text. ctermfg and bg are one-number values for the color index in the terminal. This is 0-15 or 0-7, the normal terminal colors. guifg/guibg are GUI foreground and background colors defined by #aabbcc or by X color names such as Black or Blue3. cterm, gui and term specify additional attributes for the text, for example, reverse for inverted colors or blink & such. If you want to specify that a certain style is colored like certain another style, say :hi def link <style_to_link> <will_be_colored_like_this_style> I think that's all.

http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/misc/states6.png - now with fewer bugs than before, since implementation seems to pass most of the tests now *the implementation (Oh, I segfault on <x y="&">, which can't be good) f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: Red is transitions that are parse errors, black is transitions that probably aren't ("probably" because of the parse-error-unless-it's-a-permitted-slash thing, which the graph treats as not-an-error) I can't easily have both because I only generate one arrow per transition from the original algorithm, and then delete all duplicates, so it only ends up with red+black when there are two separate transitions between the same states It's not entirely actual code - the algorithm is represented as data in OCaml, and I can generate that graph or a C++ implementation from that data http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/misc/states7.png - unless I did something wrong, that has blue lines for every transition that cannot occur if EOF is never consumed (i.e. all the transitions that are (at least partially) caused by EOF) a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d: I don't think there is any reason why that wouldn't work I've still had to manually write a few hundred lines of C++ (which would need to be ported to other languages), mostly for the entity parsing (since that's too boring to do in a more generic way), but then it generates a thousand lines of state-machine code automatically I didn't know it either, so I'm using it as exactly the same excuse ;-) I'll try to upload what I've done soonish I'm sure there must be a way to add in a new EOF state in about three lines of code, but I'm also sure they'll take a few minutes to work out... http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/misc/states8.png (Hmm, it took fourteen lines) Now I just need to make it able to generate the spec text from the algorithm ;-) wonders if people have experience of how much more time it takes to implement tree construction compared to tokenisation Because I modified the algorithm so any case which is triggered by EOF and causes a transition into the Data state, was changed to transition into the EOFData state but the relevant part inside the Data state bit of the algorithm doesn't transition into the Data state (because I didn't bother writing in the "stay in the same state" bits explicitly) so that could be considered a bug in my old-algorithm-to-new-algorithm transformation code, but it'd require too much effort to fix :-) Hmm, it's far too easy to get exponential growth in these things http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/misc/states9.png - I'm not sure why it's gone quite that bad Yes I suppose it's unhappy because lots of states emit start/end tag tokens when they see EOF, and the tokeniser can't tell what the tree constructor is going to do to the content model flag when that happens, so I assume it could end up being set to anything, which causes unpleasant growth ("I assume" = "I tell the code to assume") Looks like that is the case - http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/misc/states10.png is far better without the EOFs Graphviz (It does tend to collapse into a mass of unreadable squiggles when you get past a certain size, and I always tend to use it on things that approach that size, but I've not heard of anything else that does the same kind of thing) (Uh, "same kind of thing" = drawing graphs, not collapsing into squiggles) My entirely unoptimised C++ tokeniser (which no longer segfaults) takes about 0.4 seconds for the HTML5 spec, which doesn't seem too bad (It's certainly a bit useless, because it just computes all the tokens and then memory-leaks them away)

Anne, Sicking, Hixie, Mjs, Shepazu, AnyOneElseThatWasPartOfTheWebAPIWG - what mechanism did you use to Close Issues? I'm asking in general sorry, I wasn't clear; let me start again I'm not asking about the UI to close an Issue in the A&I db I'm wondering what process WebAPI WG used to get consensus to close an Open issue In the widgets world, we make a decision during a VoiceConf or a F2F meeting But if there are no such meetings then I presume e-mail is used Let me be more specific ... There are some Open issues re the AC4CSR spec that I want to propose be Closed. I was going to send an e-mail to public-webapps that includes a proposal to Close and a brief justification statement. I presume I would include something like "if you disagree, please respond by YYYY-MM-DD. In the absence of any objections to my proposal on YYYY-MM-DD+1, I will Close this issue" Where YYYY-MM-DD provides 5-7 days review/response time. Is something I propose above close to what WebAPI WG did? I think it creates some confusion to leave Issues Open when they are actually Closed OK, so the length of the review period needs some discussion. One weeks seems reasonable to me. Someone can always re-raise an issue Jonas, I agree 1-week between Open and Close would [almost always] be too soon Initially, I am interested in closing several AC4CSR Issues that were raised several months ago. I'm trying to think ahead a bit to the Mandelieu meeting In case Chaals puts AC4CSR on the agenda Anne, yt? Yet the sig files may have been unpacked and placed in the FS somewhere outside of the zip what if an impl wanted to delete the sig files after the zip is installed s/is installed/is verified/ space but I guess if the sig files were deleted after initial verification this wouldn't be a prob :) is it your expectaion that a signed widget must be verified every time the widget is run? why? so you expect the UA to allow widgets to share file space with other widgets? seems like a UA should effectively create a separate sandbox for each widget l8r I'll responde to your latest email; would prefer to close this before the meeting we got a *ton* of other higher priority things for this week's call

Artb, "The problem in a nutshell is that by allowing multiple signatures, >> which is something we want to do, we create a situation in which not >> all of a signed widget's files are covered by the signature" This might be ok, so long as you cannot sneak additional XML elements into the top signature e.g., (not itself signed) <signature> .... <script> evil = xhr()...</script> </signature> then, at runtime, you use XHR to read the signature extract the script I know, it's all a bit silly One can effectively change the top level signature because it is not itself signed I agree. I think we need to push Mark a bit more on it. I'm not too phased by it, which is why I did not put the text into the spec. Seems better that if the UA detects that files have been changed or modified, it should revalidate no, but it's probably a good idea to verify then every so often s/then/them.... in case they were changed via other means e.g., a widget somehow found another security hole and changed bank.wgt's content by adding a script engines should protect their widgets. it would be like one web page changing the cookies of another web page... or worst i don't think sigs should be seen as one offs yes, so long as they are careful to not allow those widgets to be tempered with s/those widgets/the content of those widgets/ right and the UA could use the sig as the way of sandboxing I gotta go.. can we pick this up tomorrow ? hi all anyone around for a discussion about an idea for a possible microformat? just reading the wiki and didn't see something similar on the exploratory disc. I'll throw it out here and pop in and out to see if it's generated any response since you all might be away, etc. problem: browsing websites with images enabled is much slower than with them disabled, but how can a web designer/developer tell the browser which images are important and which are unimportant to the content? possible solution ./  idea: a microformat that web developers can use to hint to the browser which ones to show. a Firefox/browser extension would pick up the microformat info and show those, leaving the rest on the server and not requested conclusion: browsing would be snappier on these web sites (especially on low-performance machines) while still showing the most important images in the content, etc. possible solution / alternate: the same effect may be done with a browser extension and, instead of a microformat, using the z-index to decide priority of the images but I'm not sure if that really applies as z-index does not equal priority in POSH just throwing out ideas simply: instead of "load images on sites" being a boolean, I'd like to see it be "load only high priority images on sites" to help speed up browsing, reduce bandwidth use, etc.
